        'en': {
          'about':
              '   Boysun district is a district in Surkhandarya region. Established on September 29, 1926 (merged with Sherabad district on December 24, 1962. Reorganized on December 29, 1965). Boysun district is located in the west of the region. It borders with Sariosia in the northeast, Kumkurgan in the east, Kyziriq and Bandikhon districts in the south, Sherabad district in the southwest, Kamashi district of Kashkadarya region in the northwest, and Dekhonabad district in the west. The area is 3.72 thousand km². The population is 79 thousand people (2000). Boysun District has 1 sub-district city (Boysun), 7 rural communities (Avlod, Boysun, Darband, Machai, Rabat, Sayrob, Kurgoncha). The center is the city of Boysun Nature. The northern and western part of the territory of Boysun district is occupied by Boysuntog and its branches (Belovti, Khojabozbarak, Chol mountain, Khojagurgurota, Gaurli, Sariqil, KentalaMachay mountains, Ketmonchopti, Sarimas, Suvsiztog, Kulbatog, etc.). It consists of foothills and hills in the south and east. The valleys between the mountains and the foothills have been developed. Uconite, expanded clay, carbide, limestone mineral resources were found. The climate is a dry subtropical climate. It is distinguished from other mountainous regions of Uzbekistan by its high thermal resources. The average temperature in January is 2° at an altitude of 850 m, -6° at an altitude of 3200 m, and 30° in July at an altitude of 830 m. Average annual precipitation is 150-400 mm at an altitude of 500-1200 m, 450-800 mm at an altitude of 1200 m. Vegetation period is 230-240 days. Local winds, Fyon wind, Afghan wind blow. Many rivers and streams originate from the mountains of Boisun district. The most important of them are: Sheroboddarya and its tributaries Machaydarya (Ormoncha, Jakandi, Olchasoy), Shurob, Khojabulgansoy, Punjab, Laylagansoy; Khojaipok river and its tributaries: Kurgonchasoy (formed by the confluence of Khojabozbarak, Kyzilsoy, Chindon, Ortanago streams), Halkajar (Olachopon and Qairoksoy). Besides these, there are Hangaronsoy (Boysun), Pulhakimsoy and others. Many ancient fortresses have been found in Boisun district. The largest ones are: Poykurgon, Qazimullatepa, Saribandtepa, Yalangtoshtepa, Darband, Munchogtepa, Boyrachi, Kyziljartepa, Mullatepa, Kallakorgon. Caves where primitive people lived, locations: Teshiktash, Machai, Katta Suluvkamar, Dokonkhana, Amir Temur, Iskandar Khan and other Sairob maples (in the village of Sayrob), Iron Gate (in the village of Darband), Teshiktosh gori (in the village of Machai), Dinosaur tracks, Bibishok shot, Boybulok There are historical monuments such as cave (in the village of Korgoncha), Poyonkorgon (in the village of Rabot). Wild plants include shora, yantok, jinchak, and rosehip. buttercup, yaltyrbosh, pea, tograykhan, kiikot, gulkhairi, shuvok; from medicinal plants alkor, hartol, zanjovul, olmasot, kantepar, aqshair; juniper, wild fruit trees and other trees. Gazelles, mountain goats, wild boars, lynxes, marmots, wolves, foxes, black bears, jays, partridges, hawks, eagles, falcons, hawks, owls, harriers and others live here. The population is mainly Uzbeks, as well as Tajiks. The average population density is 20.8 people per km². There are 23,899 urban residents, 55,099 rural residents. Economy. Industry is not developed in Boisun district. The district provides 0.8% of industrial output of Surkhandarya region. Important minerals: coal (Boysun), natural gas (Gajak), polymetallic ores (Boysuntog), bauxite (Khayraq), phosphorite, potassium salt (Boysun), sulfur, combustible slanes (Boysun), building materials and other main industrial enterprises: "Trust" joint-stock company, Boysun (Tuda) idol mine, small enterprises and workshops producing consumer goods. In 1994, the first enterprise producing carbide in the republic was launched in Boysun. There is an association of entrepreneurs serving the population, an association of craftsmen, 164 small enterprises, 18 joint-stock companies, \"Boysun\", \"Boysun construction\" and 256 mobile mechanized convoys, car companies, "Boysun" market. The main industries of Boisun district are cattle breeding, grain farming, forestry, alfalfa seed breeding, horticulture and vine growing. The total land area of Boysun district is 329.3 thousand ha, including irrigated land of 6.1 thousand ha. A total of 21,900 ha of cultivated fields (including dry land), 1,500 ha of perennial trees. 2.2 thousand hectares of land belonging to garden, horticultural and vegetable growing associations (1999). There are 9 collective farms (2 grain farms, 3 livestock farms, 2 alfalfa seed farms, horticulture, beekeeping, agricultural cooperative association (beef farming), 70 farmers and peasant farms in Boisun district. The main cultivated areas are occupied by cereals, vegetables, fodder crops. "Korgoncha" and "Machay" collective farms specialize in alfalfa seed production, and "Rabot" collective farm specializes in horticulture. Boisun district has 21,800 cattle, including 11,200 cows, 190,600 sheep and goats, 41,700 poultry, 184 years old (1999). Animal husbandry is mainly specialized in meat-fat-producing sheep, cattle breeding, goat breeding, beef cattle breeding (all farms). There are 25,000 hectares of forests (arches) in Boysun district (1999). There are roads connecting the center of the district and mountain villages with the main highway of the Surkhandarya region - the Big Uzbekistan tract. In 1995, the construction of the 230 km long Guzor-Boisun-Kumkurgan railway began. In the academic year 1999/2000, 18,869 students studied in 54 general education schools, 944 students studied in 2 vocational technical lyceums, 466 students studied in 1 vocational technical school. There are 83 public libraries, 11 clubs, a house of culture, and an art museum. 138 doctors and 491 secondary medical workers work in 5 hospitals with 370 beds, "Omonkhona" health center, 5 outpatient clinics, 30 paramedics, 3 village doctor\'s offices. Since 1932 \"Voice of Boysun\" district gas. comes out (number 2200). Coal, combustible silane, sulfur and others were found in the territory of the district. Boisun coal mine is located in the overburden layers. It has been used since the 1940s. Boisun Mountain has phosphorus deposits. 95% of it is used as mineral fertilizer. The district mainly specializes in livestock, horticulture and forestry products. In Boysun, there are "Boysun" breeding sheep factory, \"Sayrob\" cattle breeding, \"Darband\" sheep breeding - meat, \"Rabad\" horticulture - savzovod collective farms. The black bay horse breeding farm in Darban is the only one in our country. In Boysun, there is \"Trust\" joint-stock company, a meat and dairy farm, a bakery, a brick factory, several individual enterprises, and farms. Boysun city (20.1 thousand inhabitants) is located on the southern slope of Ketmonchopdi mountain, on the bank of Khangarangsoy, at an altitude of 1200 m above sea level. This city is the oldest settlement in Surkhandarya region. The foothills adjacent to the city were inhabited as early as the Middle Paleolithic period. The famous hole stone cave, located in the north-west of Boisun city, and its findings are described in the first part of the article. The city of Boisun itself was inhabited at the end of the 5th millennium BC. In the 1st century BC - 1st century AD, there was a powerful fortress-city called Poicalon here. The name Baysun was first mentioned in written sources in the form of "Basand" in the works of Istahri in the 10th century, in the work \"Hudud ul-Olam\" (\"Borders of the World Countries\") written by an unknown author. According to Istahri, this village with many gardens is on the road from Bukhara and Samarkand to Chaganiyan, and it is a two-day journey from Chaganiyan. In 1951, a district industrial combine was established on the basis of artels, and in 1967 it was transformed into a local industrial enterprise. In 1972, Boysun Experimental Silk Weaving Factory started working on the basis of this enterprise. There were tailoring, weaving, and artistic workshops. In 1991, departments for the production of sewing and knitted goods were separated from the factory, and the Boysun "Tong Yuluzi" sewing factory was established. In 1993, the factory was transformed into a joint-stock company "Trust". It has preparation, textile mass dressmaking and embroidery workshops. Mainly Abirik satin and silk, bekasam, knitted products, public clothes, children\'s clothes, tunics - capes, blankets - blankets are made. People\'s writer of Uzbekistan Shukur Kholmirzayev, writers - Sattar Tursun and Erkin Azam, poet Usman Azim were born in Boysun.',
          'fest1':
              '   The name of the Boysun (Baysun) Bahori Festival comes from a small city in southern Uzbekistan. Boysun looks like an average village nestled in the Baisuntau Mountains, but the main difference is that those who live in Boysun have preserved their way of life and traditions and live the same way that they have lived for thousands of years, since the pre-Islamic days.\n The Boysun Bahori Festival is a celebration of this unique culture. In the era of globalization, these traditions are being lost, and can only be found in small villages far from large cities. The goal of this festival is to gather and preserve these traditions, not only in Boysun, not only in Uzbekistan, but around the world.\n  In 2001, UNESCO named the culture of Boysun a Masterpiece of Oral and Intangible Cultural Heritage, and in 2002, the first Boysun Bahori Festival was held. Originally, the festival was held every year, but then it fell off. In 2017, the tradition was renewed.',
          'fest2':
              '   The area around Boysun is especially pretty in the spring, when the surrounding mountains are covered in green foliage and flowering meadows, and for this reason the Boysun Bahori (Boysun Spring) Festival is held in the spring. A large yurt camp is set up near the mountains, and includes workshops and stages, where folk ensembles can perform. There are also arenas for traditional sports, including kurash (wrestling), kupkari (horse game), and other competitions. A special place is given to darboz, or tightrope walking, where acrobats combine circus pageantry with theater.\n    Visitors at Boysun Bahori can also meet with masters of local crafts and works, as well as with master chefs who are experts in making traditional Uzbek dishes. Take some extra time to explore the mountains around Boysun, a unique corner among popular destinations in Uzbekistan.\n   If you want to get to know the unparalleled culture of Boysun and other regions of Uzbekistan in one place, then the Boysun Bahori Festival is the best place to be.',
          'omonxona':
              '   "Omonkhona" bal neological healing center, located in Boysun district of Surkhan oasis, is known and famous for its beautiful building, comfortable conditions, beautiful scenery, and natural healing waters. Patients suffering from diseases of the gastrointestinal tract, diabetes mellitus, cardiovascular, liver, bile, and spine are treated in the facility, which was renovated to meet world standards at the initiative of the joint-stock company "Uzbekistan Railways". is healing. Omonkhana is famous for its healing water coming from the mountain springs around. In addition to the presence of sulfur, magnesium, and nitrogen ions in this spring water, it also contains silicic acid, iron, aluminum, and many other trace elements. t has absorbent, diuretic and blood pressure lowering properties.\n Sanatorium-prophylactic "Sihatgoh" has 50 beds, where more than 700 employees are treated for a year. Treatment and rest periods are 10-15 days. Holidays are organized based on the use of passes. Heart, nervous, gastrointestinal, respiratory, locomotor, and urological diseases are mainly treated in this health center. Also, physiotherapy, massage, sauna, inhalation, paraffin, treatment with water treatments (circular shower, "sharko", rain shower, underwater shower-massage, bath), dentistry, salt room, physical education room, treatment with drugs, treatment there is a room, qualified doctors and nurses provide services to vacationers.',
